.TH "NAVIGATION.NAVIGATE" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Navigation.navigate \- Navigation: navigate() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]navigate()\f[B]\f[R] method of the \f[CR]Navigation\f[R]
interface navigates to a specific URL, updating any provided state in
the history entries list.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
navigate(url)
navigate(url, options)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]url\f[R]
The destination URL to navigate to.
Note that when calling \f[CR]navigate()\f[R] on another window\(cqs
\f[CR]navigation\f[R] object, the URL will be resolved relative to the
target window\(cqs URL, not the calling window\(cqs URL.
This matches the behavior of the History API, but not the behavior of
the Location API.
Note also that \f[CR]javascript:\f[R] URLs are not allowed for security
reasons.
.TP
\f[B]options\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An options object containing the following properties:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]state\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
Developer\-defined information to be stored in the associated
\f[CR]NavigationHistoryEntry\f[R] once the navigation is complete,
retrievable via \f[CR]getState()\f[R].
This can be any data type.
You might, for example, wish to store a page visit count for analytics
purposes, or store UI state details so the view can be shown exactly as
the user last left it.
Any data stored in \f[CR]state\f[R] must be structured\-cloneable.
.TP
\f[B]info\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
Developer\-defined information to be passed along to the
\f[CR]navigate\f[R] event, made available in
\f[CR]NavigateEvent.info\f[R].
This can be any data type.
You might, for example, wish to display newly\-navigated content with a
different animation depending on how it was navigated to (swipe left,
swipe right, or go home).
A string indicating which animation to use could be passed in as
\f[CR]info\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]history\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An enumerated value that sets the history behavior of this navigation.
The available values are:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]auto\f[R]: The default value; will usually perform a
\f[CR]push\f[R] navigation but will perform a \f[CR]replace\f[R]
navigation under special circumstances (see the
\f[CR]NotSupportedError\f[R] description below).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]push\f[R]: Will push a new \f[CR]NavigationHistoryEntry\f[R] onto
the entries list, or fail under special circumstances (see the
\f[CR]NotSupportedError\f[R] description below).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]replace\f[R]: Will replace the current
\f[CR]NavigationHistoryEntry\f[R].
.RE
.RE
.SS Return value
An object with the following properties:
.TP
\f[B]committed\f[R]
A \f[CR]Promise\f[R] which will fulfill when the visible URL has changed
and a new \f[CR]NavigationHistoryEntry\f[R] has been created.
.TP
\f[B]finished\f[R]
A \f[CR]Promise\f[R] which will fulfill when all promises returned by
the \f[CR]intercept()\f[R] handler are fulfilled.
This is equivalent to the \f[CR]NavigationTransition.finished\f[R]
promise fulfilling, when the \f[CR]navigatesuccess\f[R] event fires.
.PP
Either one of these promises rejects if the navigation has failed for
some reason.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]DataCloneError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if the \f[CR]state\f[R] parameter contains values that are not
structured\-cloneable.
.TP
\f[B]InvalidStateError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if the document is not currently active.
.TP
\f[B]SyntaxError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if the \f[CR]url\f[R] parameter is not a valid URL.
.TP
\f[B]NotSupportedError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
The \f[CR]history\f[R] option is set to \f[CR]push\f[R], and the browser
is currently showing the initial \f[CR]about:blank\f[R] document.
.IP \(bu 2
The \f[CR]url\f[R]\(cqs scheme is \f[CR]javascript\f[R].
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Set up home button
.IP
.EX
\f[B]function\f[R] initHomeBtn() {
  \f[I]// Get the key of the first loaded entry\f[R]
  \f[I]// so the user can always go back to this view.\f[R]
  \f[B]const\f[R] { key } = navigation.currentEntry;
  backToHomeButton.onclick = () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    navigation.traverseTo(key);
  };
}
\f[I]// Intercept navigate events, such as link clicks, and\f[R]
\f[I]// replace them with single\-page navigations\f[R]
navigation.addEventListener(\(dqnavigate\(dq, (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  event.intercept({
    \f[B]async\f[R] handler() {
      \f[I]// Navigate to a different view,\f[R]
      \f[I]// but the \(dqhome\(dq button will always work.\f[R]
    },
  });
});
.EE
.SS A smart back button
A page\-supplied \(lqback\(rq button can take you back, even after
reload, by inspecting the previous history entries:
.IP
.EX
backButtonEl.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]if\f[R] (
    navigation.entries()[navigation.currentEntry.index \- 1]?.url ===
    \(dq/product\-listing\(dq
  ) {
    navigation.back();
  } \f[B]else\f[R] {
    \f[I]// If the user arrived here in some other way\f[R]
    \f[I]// e.g. by typing the URL directly:\f[R]
    navigation.navigate(\(dq/product\-listing\(dq, { history: \(dqreplace\(dq });
  }
});
.EE
.SS Using info and state
.IP
.EX
\f[B]async\f[R] \f[B]function\f[R] navigateHandler() {
  \f[B]await\f[R] navigation.navigate(url, {
    info: { animation: \(dqswipe\-right\(dq },
    state: { infoPaneOpen: \f[B]true\f[R] },
  }).finished;

  \f[I]// Update application state\f[R]
  \f[I]// \&...\f[R]
}
.EE
